desmoj.core.simulator

Class QueueListStandard<E extends Entity>

  • java.lang.Object
    • desmoj.core.simulator.QueueList<E>
      • desmoj.core.simulator.QueueListStandard<E>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.beans.PropertyChangeListener, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.EventListener
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    QueueListFifo, QueueListLifo, QueueListRandom

    public abstract class QueueListStandard<E extends Entity>
extends QueueList<E>
implements java.beans.PropertyChangeListener
    Is the class summing up all the collective implementation of different queueing strategies for a queue list. It provides all the basic methods for inserting objects in a queue, retrieving objects from a queue and getting basic informations about the queue. It is used in many kinds of queue implementations e.g. in the classes QueueListFifo and QueueListLifo.
    See Also:
    QueueBased, Queue, ProcessQueue, QueueListFifo, QueueListLifo

      • QueueListStandard

        public QueueListStandard()
        Constructs an empty QueueList with no reference to its client QueueBased. This no-arg constructor is necessary to instantiate an object of this class by calling the java.lang.Class.newInstance() method. The reference to the QueueBased object making use of this queue-functionality must be provided later by calling the setQueueBased() method. The initial length is always zero.

      • insert

        public abstract void insert(E e)
        Adds a new Entity to the QueueList. Entities are inserted according to their priority in descending order. The highest priority Entity will always be first in the queue. Entities with same priority are inserted in specified order. Do not forget to call the statisticalInsert() and to set the queue for each entity as you define this method.
        Specified by:

      • remove

        public boolean remove(E e)
        Removes the first occurrence of the given Entity from the QueueList. Checks if the given Entity to be removed does apply to all restrictions on this operation. These are :
        • The given reference to an entity must not be null
        • This QueueList must not be empty, otherwise there's nothing to remove
          • If all these restrictions apply, true is returned and the Entity is removed, otherwise false is the return value because the given Entity could not be removed since one of the restrictions above was not met.
        Specified by:
        remove in class QueueList<E extends Entity>
        Parameters:
        e - Entity : The Entity to be removed from the QueueList
        Returns:
        boolean : Is true if the given Entity is contained in the QueueList, false otherwise
